<section class="bg-[#FFBF78] min-h-screen p-8 flex flex-col items-center justify-center">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8 text-gray-800 md:mt-5 sm:mt-5">bitcoin face: the wallet</h1>
    
    <div class="w-full md:flex md:space-x-8">
        <div class="w-full md:w-1/2 md:mt-4">
            <img 
                src="/oldwallet.jpg" 
                alt="Placeholder image representing human nobility" 
                class="rounded-lg shadow-lg w-full h-auto mb-8 md:mb-0"
            />
        </div>

        <div class="w-full md:w-1/2 space-y-4">
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-4 font-bold">
                Categorizing Bitcoin wallets can be done in several ways. Letâ€™s explore the different criteria:
            </p>
            
            <!-- Categorization by Device -->
            <div class="bg-[#FFEEA9] p-4 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800">By Device</h2>
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700">
                    <li><strong>Mobile Wallets:</strong> Accessible on smartphones, convenient for daily transactions.</li>
                    <li><strong>Desktop Wallets:</strong> Software installed on a computer, offering more control.</li>
                    <li><strong>Web Wallets:</strong> Accessible through a web browser, easy to use but less secure.</li>
                    <li><strong>Hardware Wallets:</strong> Physical devices that store keys offline, providing high security.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <!-- Categorization by Autonomy -->
            <div class="bg-[#FFEEA9] p-4 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800">By Autonomy</h2>
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700">
                    <li><strong>Full Node:</strong> Validates all transactions and can keep historical data. The real peers in the P2P network.</li>
                    <li><strong>Lightweight Client (SPV):</strong> Connects to a full node for transaction information, relying on its integrity.</li>
                    <li><strong>Third-Party API Client:</strong> Trusts remote servers for transaction information and privacy.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <!-- Categorization by Custody -->
            <div class="bg-[#FFEEA9] p-4 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800">By Custody</h2>
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700">
                    <li><strong>Non-Custodial:</strong> You hold your keys, offering true ownership. Examples include desktop full node and mobile lightweight wallet.</li>
                    <li><strong>Custodial:</strong> A third party holds your keys. "Not your keys, not your coins." Examples include web third-party wallets.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>
